### Open Peer Review Template

>**Notes to Editors**:
>Please adapt the template below as needed when posting your first comment in this Issue in **Phase 4. Open Peer Review**
>Ask both reviewers to provide/set up their Github@username so they can contribute to the conversation
>Introduce the reviewers to the author/translator by tagging them in a comment
>Share the URL which directs to the Preview, so the reviewers can read the lesson in their browsers
>Agree on a timeframe with the reviewers to return their comments — two months is usually reasonable. Communicate this to the author/translator so they know what to expect.
>When you see that the first review has been posted add a comment to acknowledge it, and say thank you
>Remind the author/translator not to make any revisions until both reviews have been posted — the lesson mustn’t change underneath the second reviewer

-- 

In the previous Phases 2 and 3, I provided initial feedback on this lesson, and worked with @author / @translator to complete a first round of revisions.

During this **Phase 4. Open Peer Review**, I will be inviting two reviewers from the community to provide feedback on this lesson. 

We think Peer Review is integral to publishing collaborative, productive, and sustainable learning resources. Open peer review helps maintain civility in the academic community and supports the productive sharing of ideas. In the spirit of openness, peer review discussion takes place within this Issue’s comments thread (unless an author or translator specifically requests a closed review.)

Members of the wider community are also invited to contribute constructive feedback which they may post as a comment in this Issue thread, but they are asked to first read our [Reviewer Guidelines](https://programminghistorian.org/en/reviewer-guidelines) / [Guía para revisores](https://programminghistorian.org/es/guia-para-revisores) / [Consignes aux évaluateurs et évaluatrices](https://programminghistorian.org/fr/consignes-evaluateurs) / [Diretrizes para Revisores](https://programminghistorian.org/pt/directrizes-revisor) and to adhere to our anti-harassment policy (above). 

All participants in this discussion are advised to read and be guided by our shared [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/programminghistorian/jekyll?tab=coc-ov-file).

We try to keep our conversations open here on Github. If anyone feels the need to discuss anything privately, you are welcome to email me. You can find my contact details on the [Project Team](https://programminghistorian.org/en/project-team) / [Equipo de Proyecto](https://programminghistorian.org/es/equipo-de-proyecto) / [Équipe du projet](https://programminghistorian.org/fr/equipe-projet) / [Equipe do Projeto](https://programminghistorian.org/pt/equipe) pages of our website.

